The optical properties of as synthesized S-C-dots were studied using UV–Vis and fluorescence spectroscopy (Fig. 5
                        ). In UV–Vis, absorbance peak at 287 nm is observed which is assigned to π → π* transition due to sp2 domains of CC from carbon core [16–18]. Similarly, emission behaviour of S-C-dots at different excitation wavelengths was also studied (Fig. 1S). The excitation wavelength of 360 nm resulted in maximum emission intensity. Therefore using excitation wavelength of 360 nm, emission behaviour of S-C-dots was studied at different pH which resulted in decrease in fluorescence intensity of S-C-dots as the pH of S-C-dot solution increases (Fig. 6
                        ). Overall, as synthesized S-C-dots showed maximum fluorescence intensity at an excitation wavelength of 360 nm having pH = 1. The behaviour of S-C-dots from pH 3 to 7 shows good linearity. Such response towards different pH may be attributed to various degrees of protonation/deprotonation of S-C-dots as the pH of solution changes. The decrease in pH leads to higher net surface charge and increase in hydrophilic properties of S-C-dots thus increasing their stability and dispersibility in water. This results in enhancement of fluorescence intensity of S-C-dots as the pH of solution decreases [14,16]. The quantum yield of as synthesized S-C-dots was determined to be 5.77% (Fig. 2S).
